I did not fail to be interested in the Dr A. Carlyle Excerpts,Excerpts from Alexander Carlyle’s Autobiography were pbd. in the Critic, 1 Dec. and was intending daily to say Yes to yr kind offer of sending me the Book,—when a Note came from Burton the Editor, announcing that he had a Copy on the the road for me. Copy has arrived, last night; and I find (first 20 pages especially whh are quite apocalyptic to me in the genealogical way) very entertaining indeed. A solid, vivid, effectual old fellow; with descriptions admirably clear and honest; a man very well worth hearing on the much he has seen;—and a credit to the clan withal. I did not before know he was of Annandale; of Cummertrees (with Bridekirk &c), much less. — — The late Mrs Jameson’s Father (Murphy by name, a miniature-Painter of repute)Denis Brownell Murphy ( 1763– d. 1842 ; ODNB ), Irish miniature-painter; father of Anna Brownell Jameson (1794–1860; ODNB ; see 10:196 TC to ABJ, 12 Oct. 1834
), writer, known to the Carlyles since 1834; she d. 17 March. had done a good picture of him,Possibly the miniature reproduced as the frontis. to Autobiography (London and Edinburgh, 1910); see opp above. James Kinsley noted that D. B. Murphy’s miniature was one of two (the other was by George Sanders) owned by Alexander Carlyle Bell, a descendant of Dr. Alexander Carlyle’s sister (see Alexander Carlyle, Anecdotes and Characters of the Times, ed. J. Kinsley [London, New York, and Toronto, 1973] xxii). whh I once had for a while, and sent, at Mrs J.’s request, to Edinr, to John HunterJohn Hunter (1801–69), Edinburgh lawyer; see 8:161 JWC to SS, 30 June 1835
. to try “if anybody wd give £5 for it”: nobody wd; and it came back;—wd naturally be sold among Mrs J.’s effects; but might perhaps still be recoverable, if wanted? To my recollectn, it was a bigger, opener face than that now given as frontispiece;John Burton reproduced the 1770 portrait of Dr. A. Carlyle by David Martin (1737–97; ODNB ); see 56 see above. had a still more decisive nose; and seemed to belong to a tall straight-up figure.

All in usual state here. Weather mere liquid mud,—sleep somewhat precarious again, work still rolling on. I think of trying “Turkish Baths”Turkish baths had recently been introduced into Britain, inspired by David Urquhart (1805–77; 
