I didnt go to hear Spurgeon— It rained slightly and my head ached slightly; and Lady Airlie had told me the day before; “Oh dont; please dont go to Spurgeon! it is so—nasty!”Rev. Charles Haddon Spurgeon (1834–92; 
  ODNB
), Baptist preacher and religious writer; he had recently opened the Metropolitan Tabernacle, Elephant and Castle, London; probably the largest building in England for public worship, it held 6,000. The Times, 28 March, reported on a meeting of the contributors to the Metropolitan Tabernacle building fund held at the chapel: “A vast concourse of persons had assembled, and the appearance of the building inside, now that it was complete, was truly imposing. The chief colours being white and gold contrasted greatly with the sombre appearance of the multitude.” For the outside of the building, see 142
  above
  .

We have had a terrible fire,—“the biggest,” they say, “since 1666;”—inTooley street, opposite the Custom house: it was sadly visible here for two 
nights;The fire began in Tooley St. (about 7 mi. [11 km.] ENE of Cheyne Row), Sat. afternoon, 22 June, quickly spreading through the riverside wharves and warehouses. The Times reported, 24 June: “It was not till night fell that the tremendous terrors of the spectacle could be appreciated in all their horrid grandeur. Never since the fire of 1666 had such a scene been witnessed. The whole south bank of the river from London-bridge to below the Custom-house seemed one stupendous pile of fire, glowing at its core with an intensity that made it painful to look at, and casting a ruddy glare above on everything far and near.” The fire burned for two days. For the scene at Cotton’s Wharf, Sunday morning, 23 June, see above. and a chief fireman (one Braidwood, who it seems lived in Cheyne Row)James Braidwood (1800–1861; 
  ODNB
), superintendent of the London Fire Engine Establishment; he was killed on the first night of the fire when the wall of a burning warehouse fell on him; no evidence that he ever lived in Cheyne Row has been traced. is much regret[ted]Letters omitted. all over Town. Adieu dear Brother: 
  Your Affecte


      T. Carlyle

Last night I had done my ride, by Hammersmith,Hammersmith, suburb of London about 3 mi. (5 km.) W of Chelsea. unusually soon; tea still by daylight; and was agn among heaps of Books. Larkin came in with maps;—sorrow on them (quite fallen into oblivion in my head again):—however we did make it out; and, seeing me desirous of solitude, he did not stay long.— —Today I am to ride to Woolner’s Julius Hare;
      Woolner’s bust of Hare; see TC to JWC, 7 Aug.


